items.synopsis: Days after being threatened by multiple, large bushfires, communities in the state's east are bracing for flooding as heavy rainfall continues feeding into river systems. Follow live.

title.children: Floodwaters inundate homes in Victoria's east after heavy rain swells major rivers

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Victorian Premier Jacinta Allan thanked the emergency service crews, including volunteers, who have been working in the state's east and north-east. "They started the week working on fires. Some of that fire activity continues and now in the later end of the week they are working on the flood response," she said. She said after flood levels peak, which is expected to occur around midday, teams would be better placed to assess any damage. "Teams will then be able to go in and assess the level of inundation, particularly in homes," she said. "They've not been able to get in and do that assessment yet because the floodwaters continue to rise and a number of roads remain closed in the local community." The premier said the release of water at Lake Glenmaggie and Lake Eildon had been discussed at an emergency meeting last night. She said nine people had spent the night at the relief centre at Sale, and that that personal hardship payments were available for those affected by the floods. "I want to thank local communities and local residents for heeding the warnings and making their decisions early as to how they can make themselves and their families safe in this emergency situation," Ms Allan said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Premier says flood damage will be assessed after levels  peak

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Daniel Miles Southern Rural Water has responded to criticism it didn’t react quickly enough to forecast flooding in East Gippsland. Newry dairy farmer Tim Dwyer, whose property is impacted by the floods, told ABC Victorian Mornings that the peak water body should have released water from the Glenmaggie Weir earlier. “No attempt was made to drop the level of the ‘Maggie’ weir,” he says. The ABC understands water releases from Lake Glenmaggie reached 58,000 megalitres overnight. Southern Rural Water has defended its actions, stating it worked to the information available at the time. “We ran models before the events over the last couple of days and those models were based on the high end of the rainfall range in this catchment,” managing director Cameron Fitzgerald says. “The models aren't wrong, we use the best available information that we have. “And then of course, there are variations in what actually happens, where the rain falls in the particular catchment, and how that flows. He stopped short of apologising to residents, stating welfare’s been at the forefront of all decisions. “We have managed the dam in a way that has taken the peak off this flood,” Mr Fitzgerald says. “Unquestionably the dam being there has reduced the amount of flooding downstream.”
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Water authority defends Lake Glenmaggie management

children.content: Reporting by Daniel Miles
Southern Rural Water
has responded to criticism it didn’t react quickly enough to forecast flooding in East Gippsland.
Newry dairy farmer

, whose property is impacted by the floods,
told ABC Victorian Mornings that the peak water body should have released water from the Glenmaggie Weir earlier.
“No attempt was made to drop the level of the ‘Maggie’ weir,” he says.

Southern Rural Water
has defended its actions, stating it worked to the information available at the time.
“We ran models before the events over the last couple of days and those models were based on the high end of the rainfall range in this catchment,” managing director
Cameron Fitzgerald
says.
“The models aren't wrong, we use the best available information that we have.
“And then of course, there are variations in what actually happens, where the rain falls in the particular catchment, and how that flows.
He stopped short of apologising to residents, stating welfare’s been at the forefront of all decisions.
“We have managed the dam in a way that has taken the peak off this flood,” Mr Fitzgerald says.
“Unquestionably the dam being there has reduced the amount of flooding downstream.”

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The three towns under immediate flooding threat are Newry, Tinamba and Tinamba West. Newry is is about 215 kilometres east of Melbourne, and 30 kilometres north-west of Sale. According to the latest census, the town had a population of 451 people. Meanwhile Tinamba and Tinamba West had recorded populations of 358 and 63 respectively.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Federal Labor senator for Victoria Jana Stewart says she's confident people will get behind the proposed Voice to Parliament, as the last leg of campaigning gets underway. There is just over a week until the referendum on October 14, but AEC data shows more than 900,000 Australians have already voted. Senator Stewart says polls that have the No campaign leading don't reflect what people tell her on the ground. "Lots of people as they are going past, they are saying to me 'I am already saying yes'. "There are people who are saying to me as they are walking in, it's really simple and they'll say, 'I'm voting yes but I'm not telling my friends because it has been really horrible'."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: As you may have heard, a referendum needs a double majority to pass. This is one of its key differences from a federal election. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: William McDonnell has been appointed as chief financial officer of Insurance Australia Group (IAG), subject to regulatory approval. The insurance giant let the Australian Securities Exchange know about the appointment in the last 15 minutes. Mr McDonnell will be relocating to Sydney from London to take up the role. He's joining IAG from the global governance body, the Integrity Council for the Voluntary Carbon Market, where he spent two years as chief operating officer. He built that organisation from its foundation, leading it to be recognised as the world's standard-setter for carbon credits, and he oversaw the recent release of the Core Carbon Principles ad rulebook. Mr McDonnell also spent 15 years at the general insurer Royal & Sun Alliance Insurance Group, where for the last seven years he was group chief risk officer.
